{"type":"message","id":"5d6b983f","parentId":"67c40b92","timestamp":"2026-03-24T15:16:46.382Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_t9llr0ohk6ri_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 111620\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: the (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLooking at my goals and the current state, I need to advance the research. The most immediate pending action is:\r\n\r\n\"CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\"\r\n\r\nFrom the CFI_RESULTS.md findings:\r\n- 44.8% of frequency-invariants have CFI=0 (pure noise/metaprogramming artifacts)\r\n- Only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors)\r\n- Mean CFI is 0.181 - frequency-based compression is mostly signal loss\r\n\r\nThe next logical step is to design and implement a CFI-weighted compression experiment. I should:\r\n1. Create an experiment that compares CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline\r\n2. Measure which approach better predicts next-pulse state\r\n\r\nLet me design this experiment and create the necessary documentation/prototype code.\r\n\r\nI'll create a simple Python script that:\r\n1. Loads the frequency invariants data\r\n2. Implements both frequency-baseline and CFI-weighted compression\r\n3. Compares prediction quality\r\n\r\nFirst, let me check what data I have available and design the experiment properly.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that 94.3% of frequency-invariants are contaminated (CFI<0.7), yet all invariants are currently treated equally. A CFI-weighted compression experiment is needed to test whether filtering by CFI improves next-pulse prediction quality.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate the CFI-weighted compression experiment script that compares CFI-filtered vs frequency-baseline compression for next-pulse prediction, establishing empirical validation for the theoretical insight.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n`\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n**Created:** 2026-03-24\r\n**Purpose:** Compare CFI-weighted compression vs frequency-baseline for next-pulse prediction\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\n\r\nHigh-CFI invariants (>=0.7) are true causal anchors that predict next-pulse state better than frequency-based invariants, even if they appear less frequently.\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Compression Methods to Compare\r\n\r\n1. **Frequency-Baseline (current)**\r\n   - Weight by frequency count\r\n   - All invariants equally weighted by appearance rate\r\n\r\n2. **CFI-Weighted (proposed)**\r\n   - Weight by CFI score\r\n   - Filter invariants with CFI < 0.7 (removes ~94.3% contamination)\r\n   - Remaining ~5.7% are true causal anchors\r\n\r\n### Prediction Metric\r\n\r\nGiven pulse N's compressed state, predict which invariants will appear in pulse N+1.\r\n\r\n- **Precision@K:** Of top-K predicted invariants, what fraction appear in pulse N+1?\r\n- **Coverage:** What fraction of pulse N+1 invariants are predicted?\r\n\r\n### Expected Outcome\r\n\r\nCFI-weighted should achieve:\r\n- Higher precision (less noise contamination)\r\n- Lower coverage initially (fewer invariants survive filtering)\r\n- Better signal-to-noise ratio\r\n\r\n## Implementation\r\n\r\n```\r\nexperiments/cfi_compression_experiment.py\r\n```\r\n\r\nSee implementation file for full code.\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n`\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 0\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 11:16:39\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774365406378}}
